LTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hewlett-Packard Co. moved to seizeleadership in the $4 billion computer workstation market,announcing an agreement to buy Apollo Computer Inc. for $476million in cash.   Hewlett-Packard's surprise announcement Wednesday stole somethunder from rival Sun Microsystems Inc., which announced what itcalled the most significant new products in its history.</TEXT><DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   GPA Group Ltd., one of the world'slargest aircraft leasing companies, said it will announce thelargest aircraft order in history next week, saying it plans toorder airplanes and engines worth $11 billion to $20 billion.   The Ireland-based company's chief operating officer, James M.King, said Wednesday he is ordering a mix of airplane modelsmanufactured by Boeing Co., McDonnell Douglas Corp. and AirbusIndustrie, the European joint venture aircraft maker.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Carlyle Group continued its pursuit ofFairchild Industries Inc., sweetening its offer for the aerospaceelectronics company to $243.7 million.   Wednesday's move was the second time Carlyle has raised itsoffer for Fairchild, which has rejected the investmentpartnership's previous bids.   Fairchild Secretary John Jackson said the bid was beingevaluated.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Cable television executives faced a buzz sawfrom congressional, broadcast and consumer critics who said cablecompanies are reaping billions of dollars in profits at publicexpense.   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, led the attack Wednesday at acongressional hearing, saying cable rates have risen an average of32 percent nationally since Congress lifted virtually allregulations on cable operators in 1984.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Communications Commission said itwould consider whether there is enough competition in thelong-distance market to give the American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co.more latitude in pricing.   A decision to unleash ATandamp;T, if it came, would be a major changein federal regulation of the telephone industry. The FCC statementcame Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mexico's latest $3.65 billion loan from theInternational Monetary Fund will likely improve its standing inupcoming debt restructuring talks with commercial bank creditors,bank executives said.   The executives comments on Wednesday came as negotiationsbetween the country and a 13-member bank committee are set to beginApril 19 in New York. The Mexican agreement with the IMF wasannounced Tuesday.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market rose again Wednesday, as the Dow Jones averageof 30 industrials rose 8.07 to 2,319.65, adding to its 9.71-pointgain on Tuesday.   Government and corporate bond prices finished little changed toslightly lower in sluggish dealings, while municipal bond pricesedged up.   The dollar ended mixed against major currencies in U.S. tradingafter increasing slightly abroad.   Palladium futures prices surged and other precious-metal futuresprices advanced; cocoa futures plunged; gasoline prices rose butother energy futures were mixed; grains and soybeans were mostlyhigher; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>